comment: A mapping is continuous at ` P ` in a first-countable space ` X ` iff it is sequentially continuous at ` P ` , meaning that the image under ` F ` of every sequence converging at ` P ` converges to ` F ( P ) ` . This proof uses ~ ax-cc , but only via ~ 1stcelcls , so it could be refactored into a proof that continuity and sequential continuity are the same in sequential spaces. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 7-Sep-2015.)
